description:
Digital comics version of the American Terrorist graphic novel. Published by small indy A Wave New World.

Publisher's synopsis:

A war has been waged against the American people. It’s a covert war, one that those in power hope will go unnoticed, but day by day, jobs, homes, pensions, healthcare coverage, quality of life, and civil liberties are taken away, while the gap between the haves and the have-nots grows wider and wider.

With no way out, four activists become fugitives from the law and go on the offensive against corruption and injustice. Sharing their story with the nation using social media, they inspire their followers to rise up and reclaim their country.

Story by Tyler & Wendy Chin-Tanner

Art by Andy MacDonald and Matt Wilson

description:
Featuring the first appearance of Brin.

An anthology comic by Tim Brown and Matt Trimby, Something Bizarre's one (and only) issue was printed in September 1993, back before digital reproduction when printers used film and the colour cover had to be put together with green sticky paper on a clear acetate sheet. A labour of love, it took nine months to write and draw.

1,000 copies were printed and over the course of the next few months.....nearly 10 copies were sold. Luckily November 5 was just around the corner and soon that number was reduced substantially thanks to a large bonfire.

Over the course of a year Something Bizarre gradually shifted 100 copies (many of them from Forever People in Bristol, UK) so it wasn't all bad. But one can only imagine if Matt had got his way and printed 2,000 copies on that fateful September day (as the printer had a 'special deal' on).

Something Bizarre was a game of two halves - Trimby's superb comic observations and movie parodies plus Brown's fantasy adventure - Brin. Taking nine months to produce, many of the Brin pages were redrawn up to three times as Tim had never drawn a comic before and wanted it to be perfect. It was still terrible, but it was a start.

Something Bizarre also featured an interview with Terry Pratchett.

Third volume of Brin's small press adventures.

A seven issue (ten-part) series - 'The Cult of Ka-Roos' involved Kerrus and a whole host of new characters, as the fate of the world dangles in the balance from a strange inter-dimensional entity.

Scriptwise, the high-point of Brin's small press adventures. Most issues had a highly detailed backcover illustration which would set the tone for the follow-on series - Talamander.

description:
Fourth volume of Brin and after the detailed style of Talamander, Brin's adventures begin again from scratch, with a new looser, more cartoony style.

After Talamander, Tim Brown had started work on a Brin Graphic Novel, but after struggling with the new detailed style developed for this series, abandoned it in favour of a back-to-basics new series in a simpler style. The graphic novel would later form the basis for issues 6-12 storyline 'The Box'.

The longest running small-press Brin series, totalling 24 issues (between 2004 and 2010).
